body:
After looking for an easy and fluent way of asserting on exceptions and couldn't find any, 
I came up with this code:

``` java
public class ExceptionAssert
{
    public static ExceptionAssert expectException(final Runnable r)
    {
        return new ExceptionAssert(r);
    }

    private Throwable   thrown;

    private ExceptionAssert(final Runnable r)
    {
        try
        {
            r.run();
        } catch (final Throwable e)
        {
            thrown = e;
        }
        assertThat(thrown).withFailMessage("expected exception but none thrown").isNotNull();
    }

    public ExceptionAssert ofType(final Class<? extends Throwable> c)
    {
        assertThat(thrown).isInstanceOf(c);
        return this;
    }

    public ExceptionAssert withExactMessage(final String expectedMessage)
    {
        assertThat(thrown).hasMessage(expectedMessage);
        return this;
    }

    public ExceptionAssert withMessageContaining(final String... strings)
    {
        Stream.of(strings).forEach(s -> assertThat(thrown).hasMessageContaining(s));
        return this;
    }

    public ExceptionAssert withStackTraceContaining(final String... strings)
    {
        final String trace = ExceptionUtils.getStackTrace(thrown);
        Stream.of(strings).forEach(s -> assertThat(trace).contains(s));
        return this;
    }
}
```

usage:

``` java
ExceptionAssert.expectException(() -> uut.doSomething())
                        .ofType(RuntimeException.class)
                        .withMessageContaining("something wrong")
                        .withStackTraceContaining("inner error");

ExceptionAssert.expectException(() -> uut.doSomethingElse());
```

Any use for this inside assertj? 
Do you have anything similar?
